# Average shortest distance between the nodes in graph G

# The algorithm below first finds the shortest distance between all pairs of
#  connected points, then averages these values:

nx.average_shortest_path_length(G)

# As we can see from the output below, the average shortest distance
#  between two nodes in our digraph is about 9.59, where every edge 
#  has a distance of 1 (since edges do not have weights in our case).
#  The way this is calculated is that the shortest possible path 
#  between all connected nodes is found, and then these values are averaged 
#  together. Because we have an edge distance of 1, this means that
#  on average, we have to go through about 10 nodes to get from one
#  node to another node in the network, assuming we are traversing 
#  through the shortest possible path.
Out[370]:
9.592795477759587

# Calculate the average clustering coefficient of G: (sum of all the local 
#  clustering coefficients divided by the number of node, where 
#  the clustering coefficient for a node is the fraction of pairs of a 
#  node's connections that are connected with each other)

nx.average_clustering(G)

# With an average clustering coefficient of about .41, we can say that on average,
#  if we randomly pick any node in the network,
#  less than half of its connections are connected with each other.
#  Thus, we can say that
#  the network is far from fully connected (this would mean the 
#  coefficient would have a value of 1), though it is also not completely
#  unconnected (this would give the coefficient a value of 0), but moreso
#  uconnected.

In [14]:
# From the output above, we can see that the nodes with the highest 
#  ranking are: 8, 481, 33, 18, 23, 30, 346, 99, 93 and 21.  The pagerank 
#  value for a node measures how connected it is to all other nodes in 
#  the network: thus nodes with a higher pagerank value are nodes that are
#  more connected to well-connected nodes.  Because of this, the pagerank
#  value of each node is proportional to the pagerank value of 
#  the number of nodes that point to it. At each iteration of the algorithm, the pagerank 
#  for each node is calculated as the sum of the pagerank of the node(s) pointing
#  to the given node divided by the number of outgoing nodes from the original node's
#  incoming node.  Thus, the top ten highest ranked nodes above are
#  the nodes that have the highest number of the highest connected connections.

# Citation:
# Holczer, Balazs. YouTube, YouTube, 22 May 2017, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P8Kt6Abq_rM.

# Overall conclusion of network G:
#  After performing this exploratory data analysis, we can conclude that this network is 
#  not fairly well-connected, given its transitivy and average custering coefficient 
#  values, which are both less than .5.  This observation is also supported by the 
#  value of the shortest path length being about 10, which as we explained above indicated
#  that we must go through 10 nodes on average to get from one node to another.  In 
#  the context of our dataset, this means that Amazon books, music, videos, toys, and
#  dvd's may not be majorly co-purchased together on average.  However, as we will predict
#  in part 3, future connections may arise among these items and the network could 
#  contain more co-purchased items.

# Extract features, mainly the clustering coefficient, page rank, degree centrality,
#  closeness centrality, and betweenness centrality
new_df = pd.DataFrame(index=G.nodes())

new_df['id'] = list(G.nodes())

new_df['id'] = new_df['id'].astype(int)

new_df['clustering_coefficient'] = pd.Series(nx.clustering(G))
# for each node, the fraction of all possible triangles through that node that exist

new_df['degree_centrality'] = pd.Series(nx.degree_centrality(G))  
# for each node, the fraction of nodes that that node is connected to

new_df['closeness_centrality'] = pd.Series(nx.closeness_centrality(G))
# for each node, the reciprocal of the sum of the shortest path distances from a node 
#  to all other nodes

new_df['betweenness_centrality'] = pd.Series(nx.betweenness_centrality(G))
# for each node, it is the sum of the fraction of all pairs' shortest paths that 
#  pass through it

new_df['page_rank'] = pd.Series(nx.pagerank(G))

# Then combine this new data frame by the node identity with the training set read in
#  above by reviewTrain.csv, but first use one-hot encoding to convert the
#  'group' column in the csv into dummy variables.  Note that I excluded the 'title'
#  column that was in the training csv because each product has a unique title, and 
#  thus this variable would not be useful/meaningful to use in models prediction reviews.
x=pd.get_dummies(reviews_training['group'])
reviews_training = pd.concat([reviews_training,x],axis=1)

new_df = pd.merge(new_df, reviews_training[['id', 'review', ' Book', ' DVD', ' Music', ' Toy',
       ' Video']], on='id', how='right')

# Chek if any rows have NaN values
print("Null values in columns (before any removal):")
print(new_df.isnull().sum())
print("\n")

# After this merge, I noticed that there are 15 entries that have NaN values in the 5 
#  columns corresponding to the features I extracted above.  I dropped these rows 
#  from the dataset.
new_df=new_df.dropna()

# Make the correct data type
new_df['review'] = new_df['review'].astype('str')
new_df[' Book'] = new_df[' Book'].astype('int')
new_df[' DVD'] = new_df[' DVD'].astype('int')
new_df[' Music'] = new_df[' Music'].astype('int')
new_df[' Toy'] = new_df[' Toy'].astype('int')
new_df[' Video'] = new_df[' Video'].astype('int')

print("\n")
print("done")

# Feature selection

# I used a chi-square test to find the most important features (in order) from the features
#  that I extracted above.  The test below will tell us which
#  features which are most dependent to our target variable 'review'.  
#  In the order printed below, these are variables
#  which have the highest chi-square value, indicating a lack of independence with 'review'.  

# First split newly create data frame into X and Y matrices:
extracted_features = ['clustering_coefficient', 'degree_centrality', 'closeness_centrality', 'betweenness_centrality', 'page_rank']
X = new_df[extracted_features]
Y = new_df['review']
Y = Y.astype(str)



from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, chi2
bestfeatures = SelectKBest(score_func=chi2, k=5)  
fit = bestfeatures.fit(X,Y)
dfscores = pd.DataFrame(fit.scores_)
dfcolumns = pd.DataFrame(X.columns)
featureScores = pd.concat([dfcolumns,dfscores],axis=1)
featureScores.columns = ['Specs','Score'] 
print(featureScores.nlargest(5,'Score')) 

# From the results below, we can see that the clustering coefficient variable has the highest
#  dependence with 'review', followed by betweeness centrality, closeness centrality, 
#  degree centrality, and page rank.  Note that the clustering coefficient and betweenness
#  centrality have relatively high dependence, but the other three have somewhat low scores.
#  Nevertheless, I decided to use all these five extracted variables to train my models 
#  as they could each provide some valuable information in regards to predicting our 
#  target variable, review.

# Next, I also used an extremely randomized trees classifier to select the important
#  features of our dataset, to see if the results agree with those 
#  from the chi sqare test above. This python function creates 10 (default number) trees
#  and provides each tree with a unique random sample of the dataset features.  The trees
#  then calculate their own gini index (default), and each come up with the top features.
#  The average result of all these trees is taken to provide the final list of most 
#  useful features.  The features are displayed with their order of importance
#  in the bar graph below. 

from sklearn.ensemble import ExtraTreesClassifier
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
model = ExtraTreesClassifier()
model.fit(X,Y)
print(model.feature_importances_) #use inbuilt class feature_importances of tree based classifiers
#plot graph of feature importances for better visualization
feat_importances = pd.Series(model.feature_importances_, index=X.columns)
feat_importances.nlargest(5).plot(kind='barh')
plt.show()

# From the results below, we can see that order of importance of the 
#  extracted features differs from the order chosen by the chi-square test.
#  Here, closeness centrality is found to be the most important feature, 
#  followed by page rank, betweenness centrality, clustering coefficient, and degree 
#  centrality.  In contrast, closeness centrality and page rank were in the bottom three
#  important features using the chi-square test.

In [401]:
# For part 2, I built 3 different models: a logistic regression, a support vector machine,
#  and a multi-layer perceptron.  My method for constructing each
#  model is as follows:
#  I used the grid search method to pick the best parameters for the relevant model, based
#  on the training set I created above (X/Y_train and X_train_scaled for the multiple 
#  layer perceptron). The GridSearchCV function took my 
#  training set and split it up into 5 different validation sets.  I chose
#  5 as the number of folds as this has been empirically shown to be 
#  a reasonable value that will balance out the variance-bias tradeoff inherent
#  in the cross-validation method.  This 5-fold cross
#  validation procedure built the specified model type 5 times, each time using one of the
#  five validation sets as a test set, and the rest of the 4 validation sets as training
#  sets to fit the model. The performance (mean absolute error) of all these 5 models 
#  was then averaged to give the final MAE model. The advantage to using
#  cross-validation over simply having a training and testing set is that there is always
#  a tradeoff between placing points in one of the two sets (overfitting when placing 
#  too many points in the training set and underfitting when placing too many points in 
#  the testing set).  However, with cross validation, each data point has the opportunity
#  to both be in the training and testing set.
#  After running the GridSearchCV function for the specified model type,
#  I could then see the best values for each hyperparameter
#  and the corresponding mean absolute error.  I used these parameter  
#  values to build the final model, again fit on the training set.   
#  I then predicted target values for my test set (X/Y_test and X_test_scaled for the 
#  perceptron) and used these values along
#  with the test set's actual values to compute the mean absolute error.  
#  I chose to use a separate testing set on top of using 
#  cross-validation because sometimes cross-validation may overestimate the performance 
#  of a model due to the nature of its averaging of mean absolute errors, 
#  so using a separate testing set as a way to evaluate the model may 
#  give a better sense of the model's true performace.

# Recreate network with undirected edges this time
G = nx.read_edgelist("updated_test.csv", delimiter = ',', create_using = nx.Graph(), nodetype = int)

# Read in training csv
df_part3 = pd.read_csv('linkTrain.csv')
df_part3['nodes'] = df_part3['nodes'].astype(str)    
df_part3['connection'] = df_part3['connection'].astype(int)    

# Get a list of all the node pairs in our network:
node_pairs_df = df_part3[['nodes']]
# Convert the node types from str to tuple, and then put them in a list so that we can use
#  networkx functions to extract features.
from ast import literal_eval
node_pairs_df['nodes'] = [literal_eval(x) for x in node_pairs_df['nodes']]
node_pairs_list = list(node_pairs_df['nodes'])

# Extract features, mainly the Jaccard coefficient, resource allocation
#  index, and preferential attachment score:
#  Although there are many measures that
#  can be used to determine the closeness of pairs of nodes, I chose these features 
#  because they seemed like the most relevant and best performing and
#  ones based on past research, and our goal of predicting future links between edges.
#  First, I chose the jaccard coefficient because it measures the
#  overlap between two nodes based on the intersection and union of their neighboring links.
#  I also chose the resource allocation index because it is derived from the sum of all
#  neighbors of a node, and we know that it is more probable for a node to form a future 
#  link, or in our case for an item to become newly, more commonly co-purchased with another
#  item, if they both currently have items in common that they are each co-purchased with.
#  Finally, I chose to use the preferential attachment score as it is calculated directly
#  from the product of the set of neighbors of the two nodes in question, and the more
#  connected a node is, the more likely it is to have a future connection.
#
#  Citations:
# “Jaccard Coefficient.” Jaccard Coefficient - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics, 2015, 
#   https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/jaccard-coefficient.
#
# “Preferential Attachment.” Preferential Attachment - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics, 
#   2015, https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/preferential-attachment.

# Extract network features from our list of nodes, getting a list for each feature:
jaccard=[]
resource_alloc=[]
pref_attach=[]
for node_pair in node_pairs_list:
    jaccard.append(list(nx.jaccard_coefficient(G, [node_pair]))[0][2])
    resource_alloc.append(list(nx.resource_allocation_index(G, [node_pair]))[0][2])
    pref_attach.append(list(nx.preferential_attachment(G, [node_pair]))[0][2])
    
#  Add each list as a column to our dataframe, and cast into float data type
df_part3['jaccard'] = pd.Series(data = jaccard)

#  As stated in part 2, the grid search method 
#  divided the dataset into 5 different dataset and ran the model 5 times using 
#  one of the five datasets as the testing set and the four others as a combined training 
#  set each time.  After fitting on that iteration's training set, it then calculated the 
#  AUC score, and averaged over all five iterations to give the final 
#  AUC outputed by the best_score function.  I then picked the model with the

In [344]:
# Conclusion based on the three models above:
#  As we can see from the AUC scores for the three models above, the gradient boosting 
#  classifier had the highest (and thus best) AUC score of .505, followed by the logistic 
#  regression and multi-layer perceptron, both with AUC scores of .5.  We pick the model
#  with the highest AUC score (gradient boosting classifier), 
#  because this value represents how well a model can predict
#  data points in each class.  The ROC curve is a plot of the true positive rate (recall) 
#  against the false positive rate, and thus a well-performing model has an AUC near 1.
#  Similarly, a poor model would have an AUC close to 0, which would mean that it has 
#  a low true positive rate, and a high false positive rate (meaning that the ROC curve 
#  is well below the line with slope 1, and it means that the model is predicting the 
#  opposite of the true class to which the data point belongs.)

# Citation:
#  Narkhede, Sarang. “Understanding AUC - ROC Curve.” Medium, Towards Data Science, 
#  26 May 2019, https://towardsdatascience.com/understanding-auc-roc-curve-68b2303cc9c5.

# Read in linkTest.csv and extract features just as we did for the training set
df_part3_test = pd.read_csv('linkTest.csv')
df_part3_test['nodes'] = df_part3_test['nodes'].astype(str)    


# Get a list of all the node pairs in our network:
node_pairs_df = df_part3_test[['nodes']]
# Convert the node types from str to tuple, and then put them in a list so that we can use
#  networkx functions to extract features.
from ast import literal_eval
node_pairs_df['nodes'] = [literal_eval(x) for x in node_pairs_df['nodes']]
node_pairs_list = list(node_pairs_df['nodes'])


# Extract network features from our list of nodes, getting a list for each feature:
jaccard=[]
resource_alloc=[]
pref_attach=[]
for node_pair in node_pairs_list:
    jaccard.append(list(nx.jaccard_coefficient(G, [node_pair]))[0][2])
    resource_alloc.append(list(nx.resource_allocation_index(G, [node_pair]))[0][2])
    pref_attach.append(list(nx.preferential_attachment(G, [node_pair]))[0][2])
    
#  Add each list as a column to our dataframe, and cast into float data type
df_part3_test['jaccard'] = pd.Series(data = jaccard)
df_part3_test['jaccard'] = df_part3_test['jaccard'].astype(float)  

df_part3_test['resource_alloc'] = pd.Series(resource_alloc)
df_part3_test['resource_alloc'] = df_part3_test['resource_alloc'].astype(float)

df_part3_test['pref_attach'] = pd.Series(pref_attach)
